column12: PRODUCTION OF FOCAL BRAIN LESIONS BY INDUCTIVE HEATING
column13: A metallic pellet or seed is physically implanted into the brain in a position where a brain lesion is to be produced. The seed is composed of a metallic alloy of predetermined composition capable of being inductively heated by radio frequency energy. By virtue of the composition of the alloy, the seed reaches but does not exceed a predetermined temperature, and the desired size and degree of lesion is controlled as a function of time during which the radio frequency field is in operation.

column13: 19,861. Burton, C. F., and Burton, H. Sept. 17. Tivoli billiards.-Relates to Tivoli billiard apparatus of the kind in which the ball has to traverse one or more obstructing-members c before arriving at the receiving-element e, and consists in using one or more distributors, baffles, or the like to divert the direction of travel of the ball before it passes on to the obstructing-member. The distributor g may consist of vanes g<2> radiating from freely rotatable spindles and provided with end plates g<1>, the vanes of the two wheels intermeshing. The wheels are placed beneath an opening a' in the projection channel so that a ball must fall on to the vanes, causing them to revolve and to divert the ball from its path. The distance between the spindles and their position on the board is adjustable.

column12: Improvements in or relating to Terminal Electrical Connections suitable for the Sparking-plugs of Internal-combustion Engines.
column13: 129,221. Burton, C. F., and Burton, H. Feb. 4, 1919. Wire terminals.-An endpiece on a lead for connexion to the screw binding-post of the sparking- plug of an internal-combustion engine is of hexagonal cup-shape to engage with the fixed nut of the plug so that the endpiece is not carried round when the binding-screw is tightened. In the form shown in Fig. 2, the end-piece is a metal stamping having a socket part a which receives the insulated wire which is electrically connected therewith, and a hexagonal flanged part b which is forked to pass on to the stem of the binding- post and to fit over the fixed nut thereon where it is held in place by a binding-screw and a spring washer. A plate spring may be secured to the upper surface of the end-piece to take the place of the spring washer. The fork may be dispensed with and the slot replaced by a centrally-disposed hole to receive the post. In the construction shown in Fig. 4, the end-piece is split along the line l so that it may be sprung on to the post.

Radiofrequenz-Identifikations (RFID) -Lokalisierungssysteme und -verfahren zur Lokalisierung von einem oder mehreren Gegenständen in einem bestimmten Raum
column13: Radiofrequenz-Identifikations (RFID)-Lokalisierungssysteme und -verfahren zur Lokalisierung eines oder mehrerer Gegenstände, die sich in einem definierten Raum befinden, werden hier offenbart. Eine beispielhafte Ausführungsform umfasst das Aktivieren eines RFID-Etiketts, das mit einem in einem definierten Raum positionierten Gegenstand korrespondiert, durch ein RFID-Leser mit einer RFID-Antenne. Eine erste Signalstärke und eine zweite Signalstärke der RFID-Steuerung werden jeweils von einem ersten RFID-Empfängerknoten eines ersten Knotenkanals und einem zweiten RFID-Empfängerknoten eines zweiten Knotenkanals erfasst. Eine Steuerung veranlasst einen Multiplexer abwechselnd, um an dem Multiplexer jeweils erste Signalstärkedaten von dem ersten RFID-Empfängerknoten und zweite Signalstärkedaten von dem zweiten RFID-Empfängerknoten zu empfangen. Die ersten Signalstärkedaten und die zweiten Signalstärkedaten werden dem RFID-Leser zur Verfügung gestellt und kombiniert, um den Standort des Gegenstands zu bestimmen, der sich innerhalb des definierten Raums befindet.

column12: Surgical headlight system
column13: An improved surgical headlight that includes a headband for supporting the light on the head of the wearer. The headband carries an appropriate support for frictionally engaging a ball joint member which is carried by and above a light projecting element so that the wearer can manually manipulate the light projecting element to cause the ball joint member to be rotated in the support and frictionally held in a selected position until such time as the light projecting element is manipulated into a different position. These improved surgical headlight systems preferably include means for adjusting the vertical relationship between the ball joint member and the light projecting element so that the wearer may raise or lower the light projecting means to assist in the alignment of the axis of the light projector with the visual axes of the wearer's eyes.

INTEGRAL FLEXIBLE SPINE STABILIZATION DEVICE AND METHOD
column13: Provided are a device and a method for stabilizing two or more vertebrae (11, 12) by joining the vertebrae with a flexible device (32). The flexible device is of unitary construction and includes anchor posts (34) constructed and arranged for insertion into holes drilled into the vertebrae, preferably after removing all or a portion of the pedicles from the target vertebrae. Removal of the pedicles provides an acceptable fastening site, prevents interference with the device by the pedicles, and provides native donor bone tissue, thereby obviating the need for a second surgery to harvest bone tissue from a different site, such as the hip.

column12: Gravity traction vest
column13: A gravity traction vest for secure attachment to a patient is disclosed. The patient has a torso with a rib cage having a plurality of ribs including a lowest rib, the rib cage forming at its front a generally inverted U shaped area. The vest (10) is adapted to be secured to the patient and attached to a support structure, whereby the patient is suspended from the support structure with the head of the patient in a generally upward direction. The vest (10) includes a torso surrounding member (11) having a first section (12) and a second section (13). The sections (12) and (13) are constructed of a rigid material and the first section (12) is shaped to surround a first side of the torso and the second section (13) is shaped to surround a second side of the torso. The back edge (12a) of the first section (12) is cooperatively connected to the back edge (13a) of the second section (13). A cam over center lock (19) connects the first section (12) to the second section (13), whereby the torso surrounding member (11) is attached to the patient. Straps (22) and (23) are secured to support members (20) that are secured to the torso surrounding member (11). These are adapted to be attached to a support structure for suspending the member (11) from the support structure and applying a uniform force on the member in an upward direction. In a preferred embodiment, the bottom edges (12d) and (13d) have a flanged under portion (14) and (15) that protrude inwardly toward the patient for engagement below both the lowest rib and the inverted U shaped area of the rib cage, wherein when the vest (10) is attached to the patient's rib cage, substantially the entire flanged under portion (14) and (15) is positioned inwardly toward the patient. The vest (10) also includes a foam liner (21).

column12: BORE GAUGES
column13: A bore gauge incorporates one or more electromagnetic transducers (3) housed in a shroud (1) which in use is inserted into the bore to be gauged. Each transducer (3) comprises a coil (31) and a core (37) movable within the coil (31). In one embodiment the coil (31) and the core (37) of a single transducer (3) are mounted on opposite limbs (24, 25) of a flexible one- piece machined or cast fork-like structure (23), the two limbs (24, 25) carrying gauging contacts (4) for engagement with the walls of the bore. The shroud (1) locates the fork (23) accurately and ensures that the measurement is truly on a diameter of the bore. In other embodiments, incorporating a plurality of transducers (3), coils (31) are rigidly mounted within the shroud (1) and cores (3) are mounted on flexible limbs (60) set in slots in the surface of the shroud (1), each flexible limb (60) carrying a gauging contact (4).

column12: Hypochlorite distinfectant stabilized with calcium chelant
column13: Dilute aqueous sodium hypochlorite solution is stabilized against decomposition during storage by incorporating in it a small proportion of the calcium chelate of disodium ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid. The solution preferably contains by weight at least 95 percent water, from 0.25 to 1 percent sodium hypochlorite, and from 0.005 to 0.25 percent of the calcium chelate. It may be stored for a period of many months and remains effective as a disinfectant for medical environmental surfaces. The solution may also be formulated to contain a synthetic detergent, such as sodium lauryl sulfate, 0.1 to 3 percent, and an alkaline builder, such as sodium metasilicate, to maintain a pH value above 11. Sodium hydroxide may be added to produce a pH above 12.

column12: Gravity traction device with a base support and method
column13: A device (10) for transferring stress from the lumbar spine to a rib cage of a person is disclosed. The device (10) includes support members (60 and 61) for engaging and support the person below a rib cage. The supports bars (40 and 41) support the support members (60 and 61). The support bars are positioned substantially below the support members. A seat member (30) is positioned below the support members (60 and 61). The person assumes a seating position on the seat member (30) and is also supported thereby. The amount of support provided the person by the seat member and the support member may be varied. In addition, the invention includes a method of transferring stress utilizing the device (10). The device (10) may also provide the additional feature to gain physically beneficial exercise in conjunction with gravity traction.

column12: Radio-frequency identification (RFID) locationing systems and methods for locating one or more items positioned within a defined space
column13: Radio-Frequency identification (RFID) locationing systems and methods for locating one or more items positioned within a defined space are disclosed herein. An example embodiment includes energizing, by an RFID reader having an RFID antenna, an RFID tag corresponding to an item positioned within a defined space. Each of a first signal strength and a second signal strength of the RFID tag is detected, respectively, by a first RFID receiver node of a first node channel and a second RFID receiver node of a second node channel. A controller alternates a multiplexor to receive at the multiplexor each of first signal strength data from the first RFID receiver node and second signal strength data from the second RFID receiver node. The first signal strength data and the second signal strength data is provided to the RFID reader and combined to determine a location of the item positioned within the defined space.

Ball and float valves; closing, retarding; packing, special methods of; spraying, preventing.- A self-closing valve, adapted to be opened by a float lever and closed by the pressure of fluid in the inlet, is provided with means for retarding closure, regulating the opening, and preventing shocks, noise, spraying, and leakage, and with means for stopping the valve near the end of its closing movement, until the float reaches its highest position. Closing is retarded by a conical enlargement 22 on the valve stem and a spring- pressed piston 24, the head of which slides in contact with the wall of the inlet passage while its stem engages a guiding-flange 16. The hollow piston stem is closed at its lower end, has longitudinal slots 26, which may vary in length, and is perforated at the upper end. The valve disk 20 is connected to its stem by a nut 23 of the form shown, and the length of its stem is adjusted by a nut 43, provided with a lock-nut, which also acts as a deflector to prevent spraying. The float lever 30<1> carries a roller 48 which acts on a plate 49 secured to the operating-stem 31'. The valve is stopped near the end of its closing movement by a pivoted latch carrying a roller 51, the centre of which is lifted above the centre of a roller 50 on the plate 49, so as to release the latch, by the action of the float lever 30<1> on an adjustable screw 54.

Improvements in or relating to the Jointing of Tubular Structures.
column13: 5014. Burton, C. V. March 1. Spigot-and-socket joints; sleeve joints.-Relates to a method and device for use in jointing tubes to tubes or other hollow bodies, and is especially suitable for cycle frames. The joint is made by placing a plug of deformable material within a tube, which is encircled by the article to which it is to be joined, and applying force to the plug to shorten it in one or more of its dimensions. The material used for the plug may be fusible at a low temperature. One such material is a fusible metal of 8 parts by weight of bismuth, 5 parts of lead, and 3 parts of tin ; another is a mixture of pitch, tallow, and dry plaster-of -Paris. Figs. 3 and 4 show a method of jointing together two tube ends. The plug A is placed in the end of the tube B, which extends into the end of the tube C. By means of the jaws D, D<1> the plug and the tube ends may be deformed, thereby interlocking the tube ends and producing a fluid-tight joint. End plates A<3> connected together by a transfixing- device serve to resist longitudinal expansion of the plug. After the joint has been made, the plug may be fused and run out, or may be removed by a solvent &c. In another arrangement, a liner is placed within the tube ends, which are enclosed within a jig provided with openings through which pass four compressing-jaws. In a further form, the inner tube is provided with holes, and the indentations made in the outer tube are forced through these holes. The joint may also be formed by compressing the plug in a longitudinal direction by means of rams operated by screw apparatus of any convenient type. The transfixing- device may consist of a chair by which the plug may be drawn into position. The plug may be provided with a casing of harder material, which is left inside the joint as a liner. The plug may also consist of a casing, closed by a fusible plug and containing liquid which, when the joint is formed, may be run out after the fusion of the plug. Instead of one tube end enclosing the other, both the tube ends may take into a connecting-sleeve to which they are jointed. The Provisional Specification states that the indentations may be made from within the tube.

column12: DUAL-MODE DATA CAPTURE SYSTEM FOR COLLISION DETECTION AND OBJECT DIMENSIONING
column13: A dual-mode data capture system includes a capture controller, a point cloud generator, a collision detector, a plurality of cameras viewing a capture volume, and a motion sensor to generate a detection signal when an object arrives at a capture position within the volume. The controller: activates a subset of cameras in a collision detection mode to capture sequences of images of the volume; responsive to receiving the detection signal, activates the cameras in a dimensioning mode to capture a synchronous set of images of the capture position. The collision detector: determines whether the sequences of images indicate a potential collision; and responsive to detection of a potential collision, generates a warning. The point cloud generator: receives the synchronous set of images and generates a point cloud representing the object based on the synchronous set of images, for use in determining dimensions of the object.

In one embodiment the coil (31) and the core (37) of a single transducer (3) are mounted on opposite limbs (24, 25) of a flexible one- piece machined or cast fork-like structure (23), the two limbs (24, 25) carrying gauging contacts (4) for engagement with the walls of the bore. column12: Integral flexible spine stabilization device and method
column13: Provided are a device and a method for stabilizing two or more vertebrae by joining the vertebrae with a flexible device. The flexible device is of unitary construction and includes anchor posts constructed and arranged for insertion into holes drilled into the vertebrae, preferably after removing all or a portion of the pedicles from the target vertebrae. Removal of the pedicles provides an acceptable fastening site, prevents interference with the device by the pedicles, and provides native donor bone tissue, thereby obviating the need for a second surgery to harvest bone tissue from a different site, such as the hip.

DUAL-MODE DATA CAPTURE SYSTEM FOR COLLISION DETECTION AND OBJECT DIMENSIONING
column13: A dual-mode data capture system includes a capture controller, a point cloud generator, a collision detector, a plurality of cameras viewing a capture volume, and a motion sensor to generate a detection signal when an object arrives at a capture position within the volume. The controller: activates a subset of cameras in a collision detection mode to capture sequences of images of the volume; responsive to receiving the detection signal, activates the cameras in a dimensioning mode to capture a synchronous set of images of the capture position. The collision detector: determines whether the sequences of images indicate a potential collision; and responsive to detection of a potential collision, generates a warning. The point cloud generator: receives the synchronous set of images and generates a point cloud representing the object based on the synchronous set of images, for use in determining dimensions of the object.

TAPE ELECTRODE FOR TRANSMITTING ELECTRICAL SIGNALS THROUGH SKIN
column13: TAPE ELECTRODE FOR TRANSMITTING ELECTRICAL SIGNALS THROUGH THE SKIN A tape form electrode is provided which is usable for transmission of electrical signals into the human body through the skin. The electrode is of a construction so that it can be applied to the skin to secure good electrical contact therewith and remain in place for many days despite normal movement and the normal activities of the subject such as perspiring, and washing. The construction utilizes a porous backing material which has an adhesive layer on one side thereof and over the adhesive layer a second layer which has incorporate therein a quantity of finely divided silver metal. The composition construction is of a thickness and selection of materials such that it readily "breaths" thereby permitting escape of normal amounts of perspiration from the skin of the subject. The adhesive is normally "dry" and is activated at the time of application by a suitable solvent.

DOPPELMODUS-DATENERFASSUNGSSYSTEM ZUR KOLLISIONSERFASSUNG UND OBJEKTDIMENSIONIERUNG
column13: Ein Doppelmodus-Datenerfassungssystem umfasst eine Erfassungssteuerung, einen Punktwolkengenerator, einen Kollisionsdetektor, eine Vielzahl von Kameras, die ein Erfassungsvolumen betrachten, und einen Bewegungssensor, um ein Erfassungssignal zu erzeugen, wenn ein Objekt an einer Erfassungsposition innerhalb des Volumens ankommt. Die Steuerung: aktiviert eine Teilmenge von Kameras in einem Kollisionserfassungsmodus, um Bildsequenzen des Volumens zu erfassen; aktiviert als Reaktion auf den Empfang des Erfassungssignals die Kameras in einem Dimensionierungsmodus, um einen synchronen Satz von Bildern der Erfassungsposition zu erfassen. Der Kollisionsdetektor: bestimmt, ob die Bildsequenzen eine potenzielle Kollision anzeigen; und erzeugt als Reaktion auf die Erkennung einer möglichen Kollision eine Warnung. Der Punktwolkengenerator: empfängt den synchronen Satz von Bildern und erzeugt eine Punktwolke, die das Objekt repräsentiert, basierend auf dem synchronen Satz von Bildern, zur Verwendung bei der Bestimmung der Dimensionen des Objekts.

column13: A tape electrode usable for the transmission of electrical signals into the human body through the skin. The electrode is flexible in construction so that it may be applied to the skin to secure good electrical contact therewith and remain in place for extended periods despite movement, perspiration and the presence of water on the skin surface. column13: 930,464. Writing instruments. ROLL TIP (ENGLAND) Ltd. April 5, 1961 [April 5, 1960], No. 12046/60. Class 146 (3). A retractible writing instrument, e.g. a ballpoint pen, comprises in its projecting mechanism a rotatable member 21 which is rotated step-bystep in response to successive depressions of an operating plunger 17 and has marked thereon around the periphery a series of numbers or characters which upon rotation of the member 21 are brought successively into view through a window 27 in the barrel of the instrument. As shown, the numbers and characters are 1, 2, X and may be used for making random selections in a football pool forecast. The member 21 is rotatably mounted on the rear end of a writing unit 15 and is biased rearwards in the barrel by a spring 24 which grips the writing unit near its rear end. The member 21 has four radially projecting teeth 22 and is of reduced diameter to the rear of the teeth so as to fit rotatably in a bore in the front end of the plunger 17. The plunger 17 is restrained against rotation in the barrel by splines 18 thereon which engage longitudinal grooves in a guide portion 20 mounted in the barrel. Longitudinal ribs in the portion 20 prevent rotation of the member 21 when the writing unit is in retracted position as shown. In order to project the writing unit the operator presses on the plunger 17 and teeth formed at the front end of the plunger, engaging the teeth 22 of the member 21, carry the latter forward until the teeth 22 clear the front ends of the ribs in the portion 20. At this point, owing to co-operating cam surfaces on the teeth the member 21 rotates through # revolution and when pressure on the plunger is subsequently relaxed the spring 24 urges the teeth 22 into engagement with abutments at the forward ends of the ribs whereby the writing unit is latched in projected position. A second depression of the plunger results in a further # revolution of the member 21 which then returns to the position shown wherein the writing unit is retracted. A number or character is visible in the window 27 whether the parts are in their projected or retracted positions. Reference has been directed by the Comptroller to Specification 748,897.

column13: Methods, systems, and apparatus for initializing a dimensioning system based on a location of a vehicle carrying an object to be dimensioned. Automatic ladling apparatus
column13: An automatic ladling apparatus for conveying molten metal from a furnace to a die casting machine or the like. The ladle dipper is carried through its ladling cycles by means of cooperating link assemblies mounted on an upright base or pedestal. The assemblies include a motion generating link assembly having a generating arm with an outer end adapted to move through a generally horizontal path with a downwardly curved vertical portion at one end. The other end of the generating arm is connected to a crank arm mounted on a crankshaft that is turned by an appropriate drive through a Geneva motion mechanism. The motion of the generator arm is further controlled by a rocking link connected between the arm and the base. The outer end of the generator arm is connected to a second link assembly that includes a main link connected at one end to the base and a carrier link connected to the main link at one end and adapted to carry the ladle dipper at its other end. The attitude (i.e., tilt angle) between fill, transport, and pour positions is controlled through a chain and sprocket mechanism extending through the main link and carrier link and by a cam link and crank arrangement controlled alternately by the crankshaft movement and by the rocking link movement to coordinate the ladle attitude with the path of travel between the furnace and the die casting machine.

column12: Automatic long line commercial fishing apparatus
column13: An apparatus for use with commercial long line fishing gear for receiving the long line as it is hauled from the sea, separating the gangions and hooks from the line and directing them to a storage tub or other storage means. The long line enters the apparatus through an entrance funnel and then passes through a guide funnel where the hooks are oriented substantially in a common plane. Thereafter, the line passes through a sorting gate assembly which orients the bends of the hooks in a common manner and directs them onto a rail assembly. The hooks are then guided by the rail assembly to a storage rail attached to a storage tube. As the hooks proceed along the rail assembly the ground line is drawn over a hydraulically powered sheave and directed into the storage tub.

Dimensioning system for, and method of, dimensioning freight in motion along an unconstrained path in a venue
column13: A ranging system captures successive point clouds from moving freight, and a tracking system tracks successive positions and orientations of the moving freight. A computing device correlates each successive point cloud with each successive position and orientation and time of the moving freight, combines the correlated point clouds to obtain a composite point cloud of the moving freight, and processes the composite point cloud to dimension the moving freight. Once the freight is dimensioned, it may, for example, be efficiently loaded into a container.

column12: Liquid-vapour contact columns.
column13: A liquid-vapour contact column includes an array of vertically spaced horizontal liquid-vapour contact trays having generally circumferential sides and arrangement of downcomers to conduct liquid from each tray in the array to the tray below. Each tray has gas passages to enable gas to pass into contact with the liquid. A weir 46 is disposed on the floor of at least one downcomer. Each side of the weir 46 is spaced from the corresponding side of the downcomer. This arrangement counteracts a tendency for liquid flowing along the floor of the downcomer to become detached from the sides of the downcomer, such detachment leading to maldistribution of liquid on the tray and hence to less efficient operation of the column.

column13: A bubble rake for removing the remaining steam from liquid water that is returning to heat-exchange surfaces after an initial separation from steam. The bubble rake is a channel-forming member having a cross section generally in the shape of an upside-down U. The bubble rake is disposed in a fluid-flow path so that the channel opens down and in the direction of the path. A stall zone formed by a rake traps steam in the channel, and the channel is positioned longitudinally at an angle with the horizontal so that the trapped steam migrates to its high end, where an opening allows the trapped steam to join the steam previously separated from the water. Extrusion device for rocket motors and the like
column13: 1,005,886. Rocket motors; plastic propellent charges. ATLANTIC RESEARCH CORPORATION. April 18, 1962, No. 14986/62. Heading F3A. A rocket motor comprises a fuel tank 10, extrusion device 13 and combustion chamber 14, plastic monopropellent being forced by a piston 12, driven by gas from a pressurized container 15, through extrusion passages 13a, 13b and 13c to burn in chamber 14. Several embodiments of the extrusion device are described, in each of which the cross-sectional areas of the extrusion passages and/or their lengths are so chosen that the rate of extrusion of monopropellent is substantially the same peripherally and centrally of the device. The extrusion device in the motor of Fig. 1 is also shown in Fig. 2 where each passage is of equal length, but the cross-sectional areas of the passages increase from that in the centre to those in the outermost ring. In Fig. 5 the outlet of the device is of truncated conical form whereby the peripheral passages are shorter than the central passage although the cross-sectional area of each passage is the same. Preferably the extrusion device is made of material having low thermal conductivity, such as ceramics and fireclays, to prevent burn-back of the propellent within the extrusion passages. Particularly suitable are materials of low thermal conductivity which gasify at high temperature, such as polyamides, cellulose esters and ethers, polyesters and the like. Finely divided solid organic or inorganic compounds with good gasifying properties may be added to the above mentioned basic materials, examples being oxamide, melamine, anthraquinone and calcium, sodium and ammonium phosphate, carbonate and bicarbonate. Alternatively the device may be of a non-gasifying refractory felted, fibre, flake or woven material such as asbestos, fibreglass, mica to which is added a suitable gasifying material such as an organic polymer. Compositions of suitable plastic monopropellents are as described in Specification 972,723.

column13: 775,095. Endless conveyers; rollerways. BRITISH WEDGE WIRE CO., Ltd. Aug. 26, 1953 [May 26, 1952], No. 13287/52. Class 78 (1). An elevator comprises at least one endless chain carrying brackets inclined in a direction laterally of the plane of movement of the chain for supporting packages thereon for gravity discharge, the packages being retained on the brackets during conveyance between loading and unloading stations by stationary guide rails disposed adjacent the lower ends of the brackets and extending parallel to the conveyer for sliding engagement by the packages. As shown, the elevator comprises two pairs of chains 1, 2 driven in unison, brackets 13 being secured across each pair of chains so as to form opposed pairs in adjacent runs of the two pairs of chains to support the packages 14 for elevating or lowering between the loading and unloading stations 15, 16. The packages 14 are fed to the elevator by a rollerway 18 provided with a pair of out-of-phase stops 25, 26 operated by cams 27, 28 driven from the elevator which allow a package to pass at the correct time for receipt by the elevator. The brackets of each pair pass on opposite sides of a narrow extension 48 of rollerway 18 to pick up the packages. Each bracket has a series of rollers 17 mounted on it, the package running down the rollers until it abuts a stationary guide rail 19 along which it slides during its elevation from station 15 to station 16. At station 16 rail 19 is discontinued so that the package can run off the brackets 13 on to a rollerway 20 pivotally mounted at 21 and provided with an extension 22 adapted to be engaged by a lug 46 on an extension 44 of one of the brackets 13 of each pair so that the adjacent end of the rollerway follows each pair of brackets until discharge is complete, after which the rollerway is released and falls back under control of a damper 50 and a counterweight 51. The brackets 13 are mounted at each side by means of a gusset plate 38 to which is secured a strip 39 bushed at 42 to receive a cross-bar 40 of the chains 1 or 2, and slotted at 43 to receive another cross-bar 41 whereby allowanace is made for the reduced spacing between the cross-bars when passing over sprockets. A switch 31 is arranged so as to be actuated to switch-off the drive if a package is incompletely received by a pair of brackets 13 from the rollerway 18. A similar switch (not shown), is arranged where the package passes from the brackets 13 to the rollerway 20 to switch-off the drive if the package does not clear the brackets sufficiently quickly. The elevator may be used as a lowerator in which case descent is by gravity, the rollerways and the brackets 13 being oppositely inclined to that shown. The rollerway 20 is then biased upwardly and arranged to follow the brackets downwards and the switches are arranged to operate electromagnetic brakes. Rollerways 18 and 20 may be arranged on the same side of the elevator instead of on opposite sides, in which case brackets 13 are oppositely inclined. Alternatively the brackets 13 may be pivotally mounted and provided with means engageable at will by either of two rollerways 20, located on opposite sides of the elevator, such engagement causing the brackets to tilt towards the engaged rollerway. According to the Provisional Specification, each pair of chains may extend in the same plane instead of in parallel planes, the brackets 13 then extending in the direction of the plane of the chains, i.e. at right angle to that shown.

An electromagnetic contactor has auxiliary contacts which are operated through a cam device responsive to movement of a main contact carrier. A box-shaped insulating housing 10 receives the movable contact assembly 11 and is closed by a cover 12 which supports two rows of fixed contacts 30 for co-operation with contact bridges 25 on a contact carrier 20 of the assembly 11. The carrier 20 is secured to the armature 22 of an electromagnet 18, 47 and has legs 21 slidable in guideways 28 of the housing 10. Springs 50 compressed between the cover 12 and arm 53 on the carrier 20 bias the armature and contact carrier to the deenergized position in which cam slots 55 in protuberances of the carrier retain pins 59 on surfaces 71 thereof. When the coil 18 is energized to attract the armature 22 and close main contacts 25, 30 the inclined faces of the slots 55 move the pins 59 to the Fig. 5 position. Each pin 59 projects from an auxiliary contact unit 58 in a transparent insulating casing 70 which has six fixed contacts 76 and up to three contact bridges 85 in a slide 88 from which the pin 59 extends. The fixed contacts 76 have bent terminal ends outside the casing 70 which may be reversed to charge the auxiliary contact arrangement. In the extreme positions of the armature and contact carrier 20, the pins 59 lie in parts 71, 72 of the slots 55 in which the sides are parallel to the direction of movement of the contact carrier so that there is no resultant force on the carrier in these positions.

column12: SHEET INSPECTION AND MARKING SYSTEM
column13: "SHEET INSPECTION AND MARKING SYSTEM" A method and aparatus for inspecting and marking flawed sheet material is disclosed. Sheet material is moved from a supply along its length through a path to a cutter. The sheet material is visually inspected as it moves along its path, and a temporary electrically conductive mark is applied to the moving material at a predetermined distance away from any flaw that appears in the sheet material. The temporary mark is electrically detected at a position along the path the ;same predetermined distance away from the outter as the flaw moves into the cutter, and as the last portion of the segment to be cut from the sheet material moves to the cutter, the sheet material is marked with a permanent mark. The sheet material is then cut and folded, and the permanent mark is located at a predetermined position in the folded segment of sheet material, no matter at which location in the segment of the sheet material the flaw appears.

column12: Arbiter circuits with metastable free outputs
column13: A high-speed low-power-consumption two-input arbiter circuit comprises two input inverters, two inverters cross-coupled to form a latch and two additional inverters that drive a difference detector. The detector responds only to a voltage difference on its inputs that exceeds a specified value. In this way, signals are blocked from appearing at the outputs of the detector while the latch is in a metastable state. Additionally, an n-input arbiter circuit comprises (n-1)+(n-2)+ . . . +[n-(n-1)] two-input arbiter circuits and logic circuitry connected to the outputs of the two-input circuits for supplying a priority signal to one and only one at a time of n output terminals of the n-input circuit.

column13: A bubble rake for removing the remaining steam from liquid water that is returning to heat-exchange surfaces after an initial separation from steam. The bubble rake is a channel-forming member having a cross section generally in the shape of an upside-down U. The bubble rake is disposed in a fluid-flow path so that the channel opens down and in the direction of the path. A stall zone formed by a rake traps steam in the channel, and the channel is positioned longitudinally at an angle with the horizontal so that the trapped steam migrates to its high end, where an opening allows the trapped steam to join the steam previously separated from the water.

Sheet inspection and marking system
column13: A method and apparatus for inspecting and marking flawed sheet material is disclosed. Sheet material is moved from a supply along its length through a path to a cutter. The sheet material is visually inspected as it moves along its path, and a temporary electrically conductive mark is applied to the moving material at a predetermined distance away from any flaw that appears in the sheet material. The temporary mark is electrically detected at a position along the path the same predetermined distance away from the cutter as the flaw moves into the cutter, and as the last portion of the segment to be cut from the sheet material moves to the cutter, the sheet material is marked with a permanent mark. The sheet material is then cut and folded, and the permanent mark is located at a predetermined position in the folded segment of sheet material, no matter at what location in the segment of the sheet material the flaw appears.

column12: Display screen translator
column13: A system and method are provided for audibly interpreting a screen display. The method comprises: locating a display interpreter (DI) with a tactile matrix of sensors overlying a display screen; in response to sensing a proximate pointer, accepting a tactile matrix region selection; loading a first reference map, cross-referencing DI tactile matrix regions with a first field of screen icons; loading a second reference map, cross-referencing screen icons with audible recordings identifying the screen icons; mapping a screen icon to the selected tactile matrix region; and, audibly identifying the mapped screen icon. That is, the DI uses the second reference map to cross-reference the located screen icon to the audible recording identifying the screen icon, and plays the recording. In one aspect, the DI can be located over a touchscreen with touchscreen icons. Then, the method may further comprise engaging a touchscreen icon.

column12: Process for generating gases from monopropellants and apparatus therefor
column13: A plastic extrudable monopropellant having sufficient cohesive strength to remain a formed shape comprises a finely divided, insoluble, solid oxidizer, in an amount sufficient to maintain active combustion of the monopropellant, in a continuous matrix of an oxidizable, substantially non-volatile, organic liquid fuel. A gelling agent may be incorporated. Possible liquid fuels are hydrocarbons, esters, alcohols, ethers, aldehydes, amines, nitriles, phosphorus-containing compounds, sulphur-containing compounds and viscous liquid polymers. Suitable oxidizers are inorganic salts such as sodium and lithium perchlorates and metal peroxides. Gelling agents include natural and synthetic polymers, cellulose esters, cellulose ethers, metal salts, casein, gum, gelatine and clays. Organic gelling agents are preferred. Finely divided metal powders, such as Al, Mg, Zr, B, Be, Ti, Si may be incorporated as additional fuel. In an example, the monopropellant comprises ammonium perchlorate, viscous polyisobutylene, dibutyl phthalate and copper chromite. In another example, polyvinyl chloride was mixed with dibutyl sebacate and heated to form a gel, the gel was then cooled and loaded with ammonium perchlorate. Specifications 972,723, 972,724 and 1,005,886 are referred to.

column13: Methode et appareil d'inspection et de marquage de materiau en feuilles defectueux. Un materiau en feuilles (10) avance a partir d'une alimentation (11) sur sa longueur par un trajet determine vers une decoupeuse (22). Le materiau en feuilles est controle visuellement au fur et a mesure qu il se deplace le long du trajet, et une marque temporaire electriquement conductrice (21) est appliquee sur le materiau mobile a une distance determinee de toute defectuosite (19) qui apparait dans le materiau en feuilles. La marque temporaire (21) est detectee electriquement par un detecteur (29) en une position le long du trajet a la meme distance predeterminee de la decoupeuse (22) lorsque la defectuosite arrive vers la decoupeuse (22), et lorsque la derniere portion du segment (28) a couper du materiau en feuilles se deplace vers la decoupeuse (22), le materiau en feuilles etant marque avec une marque permanente (30). Le materiau feuilles est ensuite coupe et plie, et la marque permanente (30) est placee en une position predeterminee dans le segment plie de materiau en feuilles, quelle que soit la position dans le segment (28) du materiau ou apparait la defectuosite (19).

column12: SHEET PRODUCTION SYSTEM
column13: "SHEET PRODUCTION SYSTEM" Sheet material is taken from a supply, moved along its length to a cutting station, an edge thereof is hemmed as it moves toward the cutting station, the sheet material is cut into segments, and the cut segments are moved parallel to their cut edges, the cut edges are hemmed, and the segments are folded. At the cutting station the leading portion of the sheet material is gripped and pulled from the entrance to the cutting station to the other side thereof, a slack bar is moved downwardly into the segment of sheet material in the cutting station to form slack in the segment, the sheet material is clamped adjacent the entrance to the cutting station and the segment in the cutting station is clamped against parallel conveyor tapes. A cutting disc is drawn across the sheet material at the entrance to the cutting station, and the parallel conveyor tapes move the sheet parallel to its cut edges to a hemming station where the edges are folded and hemmed.

column12: Improvements in and relating to discharging and loading means for hoists and elevators
column13: 779,405. Endless platform elevators; rollerways. BRITISH WEDGE WIRE CO., Ltd. Aug. 26, 1953 [May 26, 1952], No. 23575/53. Divided out of 775,095. Class 78 (1). Packages are discharged from or loaded on to an elevator, of the kind comprising an endless chain or chains to which brackets or platforms are attached at intervals for supporting the packages, by the provision of a transverse conveyer, e.g. a gravity rollerway, which is pivoted at one end and has its free end co-operating with the elevator so as to follow the movement of the brackets or platforms during discharging or loading of the packages, the pivotal movements of the transverse conveyer being controlled by damper means. As shown, the elevator comprises a pair of chains 2 carrying a set of platforms 8, each of which is the full width of the packages and comprises a plurality of fingers formed by rollers 9 carried on cantilever supports 13, 14, the supports increasing in height from one end to the other of the platform so that the rollers 9 are disposed in an inclined plane. The supports 13, 14 are carried at each side by a strip 16 having a hole 17 and a slot 20 for mounting on two cross-bars of the chains with allowance for reduced spacing of the bars at the sprockets as in the previous embodiment. The lower station consists of a rollerway 33 feeding to a set of roller fingers 32 arranged in interdigital relationship with the rollers 9. The upper station consists of a pivoted rollerway 22 constructed and arranged as described in Specification 775,095, but arranged on the same side of the elevator as the rollerway 33 of the lower station. For elevating, stops 36, 37, operated by cams driven from the elevator as in the previous embodiment, allow the packages to pass one at a time to the platforms 8, which are oppositely inclined to the rollerway 33. As each package passes on to a platform, it raises a pivoted flap 43 which drops down behind it, a tail 44 on the flap engaging a stop 45 to retain the package on the platform. As the platform rises guides (not shown) prevent the package running off until rollerway 22 is reached, the lag (not shown) on the platform engaging the extension 24 of rollerway 22 as in the previous embodiment. The pivoted flap 43 serves to prevent jamming at the lower station since if a package is incorrectly positioned on the platform 8 it raises the flap 43 as it is elevated whereupon the tail 44 of the flap actuates a switch 48 arranged to switch off the elevator driving motor. A switch 49 also for switching off the motor is actuated by packages remaining beyond a certain length of time on the platforms 8 at the upper station. The elevator may lower packages simultaneously with elevating other packages by arranging a pivoted rollerway on the return run of the chains 2, similar to rollerway 22 but arranged to follow the platforms downwardly and return upwardly, and a rollerway at the lower end of the return run sloping oppositely to the rollerway 33. The elevating run may deliver to an upper station on the opposite side to the lower station as disclosed in the previous embodiment, or to either of two upper stations arranged on opposite sides of the elevator by having the platforms 8 pivotally mounted, also as disclosed in the previous embodiment. When delivering only to a station on the opposite side of the elevator, flap 43 is dispensed with.

column12: Annealing lehr
column13: An annealing lehr comprised of a plurality of serially arranged heating and cooling sections which form a continuous treating chamber through which the ware passes during the annealing operation. An endless foraminous conveyor belt moves through the treating chamber and supports the ware to be annealed, with both the charging and return flights of the belt being located within the heating section to pre-heat the return flight. At least one burner is mounted adjacent the top and at each side of each heating section, and the burners fire directly into a duct which communicates with the inlet of a fan positioned centrally above the treating chamber. The circulating system includes down ducts at each side of the treating chamber and electrical heating elements can be located in the down ducts for providing the necessary heating, in lieu of the gas burners.

column12: INTRAVENOUS FLUID HEATER
column13: A compact and highly efficient intravenous fluid heater includes a heat exchanger assembly, sensors for sensing respective temperatures of entering and exiting fluids of the flow path, a controller for controlling the heat generated by the heat exchanger assembly, based upon the temperatures of the exiting fluids, heating of the fluid in the flow path by the heating element so as to cause the fluid in the flow path to be substantially uniformly heated to a desired infusion temperature prior to exiting the heater. The heat exchanger assembly uses thin film heating elements having a predetermined set temperature and that transfers heat directly to a standard intravenous tube coil wrapped around the battery housing. The intravenous fluid heater is located in a housing with the intravenous fluid lines extending there from for standard connection with an intravenous line or source of intravenous fluid.

column12: Automatic focusing system
column13: In a system which automatically analyzes laboratory slides, the adjustable objective lens is automatically focused. A beam splitter splits light from the slide into two parts. One slide image is projected to an actual image plane where it is converted into electrical signals representing the optical characteristics of the slide. The other slide image is projected to a parfocal image plane at which two light sensing devices for the focusing system are positioned. One light sensing device is in front of the parfocal image plane and the other is behind the parfocal image plane. These light sensing devices produce electrical signals representing the position of the actual image plane with respect to the desired image plane. The electric signals are differentiated and then applied to a comparator which supplies pulses to a stepping motor which moves the objective lens. The coupling between the stepping motor and the objective lens includes an eccentric member which translates the objective lens with no sliding friction. This allows very accurate positioning of the objective lens.

column12: Improvements in or relating to the surface treatment of metals
column13: An orthophosphate coating is formed on a surface composed of iron, zinc, cadmium or an alloy thereof by treating the surface with an aqueous solution containing orthophosphate ions, zinc ions, an oxidizing accelerator and a molecularly dehydrated orthophosphate, said dehydrated orthophosphate being maintained in the solution in a minor amount (calculated as PO4) relative to the orthophosphate content (calculated as PO4). Examples of suitable dehydrated orthophosphates are metaphosphoric acid, metaphosphates, polymetaphosphates, pyrophosphoric acid, pyrophosphates and polypyrophosphates. Oxidizing accelerators mentioned are nitrates, chlorates and nitroguamide. Fluoride ions may also be present in the solution. Specification 768,443 is referred to.

column12: Aseptic packaging
column13: An aseptic package of a material susceptible to bacterial or viral infection utilizes a film or sheet of a plastic packaging material having a biocidal agent dissolved or dispersed therein. The biocidal agent comprises 10,10-oxybisphenoxarsine or a biocidal derivative or analog thereof, in an amount sufficient to inhibit biocidal activity in the contents of the package. The biocidal agent is present in solution in or in combination with a plasticizer for the plastic sheet or film in an amount from 0.001 to 5.0% by weight of the plastic. The sheet or film is a hydrocarbon-based material, such as a polyalkylene resin or polyolefin, e.g., polyethylene or polypropylene. The biocidal agent is present in solution in or in combination with a plasticizer for the plastic sheet or film. The enclosed material may be an organic product, such as a food or a plant or may be formed in the shape of a dispensible liner for bath tubs. The utilization of the packaging sheet or film may also be considered as a novel method of inhibiting bacterial or viral growth in an organic material wherein the organic material is enclosed in a package of a film or sheet of a plastic packaging material having a biocidal agent dissolved or dispersed therein.

column12: Command selection in a packet forwarding device
column13: Packet modification is performed in the switch fabric by selecting a conditional command belonging to a set of commands for modifying a packet. The set of commands is identified based on an index value, and selecting a conditional command belonging to the set of commands is based on a mask value, where the index and mask values are determined based on data in the packet undergoing modification, such as the packet's source and destination, or incoming label. Among other advantages, controlling packet modification in the switch fabric through selecting a conditional command belonging to a set of commands allows multiple sets of commands to be replaced with a single set of commands, resulting in a more efficient use of available external memory.

column12: Scanning minor stabilizer
column13: The invention provides a scanning mirror system with line of sight stabilization. In one embodiment a mirror and a balance member are mounted to rotate and the mirror is coupled by means of gear teeth to the balance member so that the inertia of the balance member tends to compensate for the inertia of the mirror. The mirror is arranged to be rotated by a drive motor and a gyro, driven at twice the mirror angle, is arranged to detect rotational movement of the mirror. The gyro is connected in a feedback control system with the drive motor in order to tend to maintain the mirror stationary when the mirror is not being driven through a desired angle by the drive motor.

column12: Improvements in or relating to the surface treatment of metals
column13: A conversion coating is produced on a metal surface by spraying, the spraying being performed at least twice and the duration of each spray application being controlled so that the total time between the first and last applications during which the surface is out of contact with the spray is greater than the total time during which the surface is in contact with the spray. Coatings may be produced using phosphate solutions; solutions containing aliphatic or aromatic dicarboxylic and hydroxycarboxylic acids, such as oxalic, malonic and tartaric acids; solutions containing aromatic sulphonic acids; and solutions containing chromates. In the two forms of apparatus described, (1) the articles are subjected to a spray which is fed intermittently with solution through a rotating-disc valve, and (2) the articles are moved through spaced spray-zones produced by a plurality of sprays. column12: RECEPTACLE POUR ACCESSOIRES CHIRURGICAUX A JETER
column13: Le réceptacle pour objets chirurgicaux à jeter après usage, tels que des aiguilles ou des lames de scalpel, comprend un fond rectangulaire garni d'adhésif, un couvercle et deux matrices constituées par des panneaux fixés le long des côtés du fond. Les matrices sont découpées pour former des cases de différentes dimensions pour y mettre les objets. Pour l'emploi, une matrice est enlevée et est jetée tandis que l'autre est repliée sur, et fixée à la face enduite d'adhésif du fond. Les objets déposés dans les cases de la matrice sont retenus par le revêtement adhésif du fond des cases. Quand toutes les cases sont remplies ou quand l'opération chirurgicale est terminée, le couvercle garni d'adhésif est replié sur la matrice pour fermer les cases avec les objets qu'elles contiennent De préférence, le couvercle est transparent pour permettre d'identifier et de compter les objets une fois que le réceptacle est fermé.

column12: Transporter segmentation for data capture system
column13: The transportation and storage of objects such as packages may require knowledge of the dimensions of a package. Such information may be employed to optimize the use of available space in a container (e.g. a trailer) or to determine a shipping or storage cost for the package. Package dimensions, however, may not be known in advance and workers may therefore be required to obtain package dimensions by manually measuring the packages which can be time-consuming and error prone with even systems for automatically measuring package dimensions suffering from reduced accuracy, for example when measuring packages in motion or packages with dark (e.g. black) surfaces. The aim of this application is to overcome these problems and consists of a server comprising a memory storing a data point cloud, a processor connected with the memory and configured to obtain the point cloud from the memory, the point cloud including a depiction of the object to be dimensioned. A bounding box corresponding to the object is generated and point densities for each of a plurality of slices adjacent to a surface of the bounding box are determined. A surface corresponding to the one of the slices with the greatest point density is selected and used to update the bounding box corresponding to the object resulting in an updated bounding box. The processor may be configured to generate the bounding box by obtaining, from the point cloud, a set of positions associated with a transporter of the object and based on these positions select. a first portion of the point cloud excluding the body of the transporter by generating a cutting plan corresponding to a forward surface of a mast of the transporter and discarding points on a predetermined side of the cutting plane. A second claimed invention comprises storing calibration data and obtaining a point cloud depicting a capture volume containing a transporter having a body and a holder carrying an object to be dimensioned. A set of positions associated with the transporter is obtained based on the set of positions and the calibration data and a first portion of the point cloud excluding the body of the transporter and a mast of the holder is selected. A second portion of the point cloud from the first portion is selected based on the calibration data excluding a base of the holder and the object is dimensioned based on the second portion of the point cloud.

column12: Automatic ladling apparatus.
column13: An automatic ladling apparatus for conveying molten metal from a furnace (F) to a die casting machine (C) or the like. The ladle dipper (L) is carried through its ladling cycles by means of cooperating link assemblies mounted on an upright base or pedestal (10). The assemblies include a motion generating link assembly having a generating arm (52) with an outer end adapted to move through a generally horizontal path with a downwardly curved vertical portion at one end. The other end of the generating arm (52) is connected to a crank arm (51) mounted on a crankshaft (48) that is turned by an appropriate drive through a Geneva motion mechanism (43-46). The motion of the generating arm (52) is further controlled by a rocking link (54) connected between the arm (52) and the base (10). The outer end of the generating arm (52) is connected to a second link assembly that includes a main link (60) connected at one end to the base (10) and a carrier link (62) connected to the main link (60) at one end and adapted to carry the ladle dipper (L) at its other end. The attitude (i.e. tilt angle) between fill, transport, and pour positions is controlled through a chain-and-sprocket mechanism (10 1 -108) extending through the main link (60) and carrier link (62) and by a cam link (115) and crank arrangement (110) controlled alternately by the crankshaft movement and by the rocking link (54) movement to coordinate the ladle attitude with the path of travel between the furnace and the die casting machine.

column12: Dual-mode pressure-sensing illumination mat
column13: Systems and apparatuses for dual-mode pressure-sensing and illumination mats are provided. The systems include a surface that includes a plurality of row wires and a plurality of column wires forming intersection points. At the intersection points, the systems include a pressure sensor configured to sense a pressure exerted upon the surface and a light emitting diode (LED) connected in parallel. The systems include a controller coupled to the selector and configured to control operation of the surface, wherein the controller is configured to operate in one of a pressure-sensing mode or an illumination mode. When the controller is configured to operate in the pressure-sensing mode, the controller scans pressure values provided by the pressure sensors. When the controller is configured to operate in the illumination mode, the controller configures the surface to enable the LEDs in accordance with an illumination pattern.

column12: Nörotrofinlerin aritilmasi.

Bu yöntemler nörotrofinlerin daha az istenen çesitli yanlis katli, büyüklüklü, glikozilatli ya da yüklü biçimlerinden ayrilmasi için araçlar saglamaktadir. column12: Methods and system for enhanced RFID direction finding
column13: At least some embodiments of the present invention are directed to RFID reader systems, readers, and/or arrangements configured to estimate a directional bearing of an RFID tag. In an embodiment, the present invention is an RFID arrangement configured communicate with an RFID tag via a primary transmit and receive signals and to contemporaneously determine a plurality of RSSI levels of the RFID tag over a 360-degree azimuth range via a plurality of secondary receive signals.

column12: Low damping high strength polymer with long chain branching for use in anti-vibration applications
column13: A low damping high strength polymer with a blend of a terpolymer and a tetrapolymer utilizing ethylene, propylene, and non-conjugated dienes. This polymer allows for the creation of products with high diene contents and broad molecular weight distributions while utilizing a continuous flow reactor and a known catalyst. The polymer allows for these products to be made without gelling or fouling of the reactor, which are problems known in the art.

column13: A voltage translator containing a bipolar transistor (Q1), a rectifier (10), a resistor (R1), and a first clamp (12) converts an input voltage (V.sub.I) into one or more output voltages of restricted voltage swing. The first clamp clamps the emitter voltage of the transistor when it is turned on. In one version, the translator includes a second clamp (14) that clamps the collector voltage of the translator when it is turned off. The translator then provides an output voltage (V.sub.O) inverse to the input voltage. In another version, the first clamp is connected between a voltage supply (V.sub.EE) and the emitter of the transistor. Its collector is connected directly to another voltage supply (V.sub.CC) so that the translator only makes non-inverting translations.

column12: Process to isolate recombinant human neurotrophin, neurotrophin composition and process for purifying neurotrophin
column13: In the present invention, there is disclosed a process to isolate a recombinant human neurotrophin from a mixture containing other proteins and a neurotrophin variant wherein said neurotrophin variant being selected from the group consisting a misfolded variant an incorrectly proteolytically processed variant, or a glycosylation variant, wherein the separating comprises loading the mixture containing the neurotrophin and a misfolded variant, an incorrectly proteolytically processed variant, or a glycosylation variant of that neurotrophin onto a hydrophobic interaction chromatography resin and eluting the neurotrophin from the resin under conditions in which the neurotrophin separates from the variant or variants. The isolation process further comprises separating the neurotrophin from its chemical variants using high performance cation exchange chromatography resin wherein the high performance cation exchange chromatography separating step comprises loading a mixture comprising the neurotrophin and a chemical variant of that neurotrophin onto a high performance cation exchange chromatography resin and eluting the neurotrophin from the resin under conditions in which the neurotrophin separates from the chemical variant.

column12: Improvements in radar apparatus
column13: 1,107,340. Pulse radar. SPERRY RAND CORPORATION. 4 Aug., 1965, No. 33330/65. Heading H4D. In a monopulse tracking radar transmitting a microwave beam on a positionable axis and producing two target echo signals of the same frequency, one echo signal (#) 7 having an amplitude representing target deviation from the beam axis and having a phase relative to the other echo signal (A) 8 representing the sense of such deviation, a modulator 6 causes amplitude modulation of signal 7 at a frequency f, a hybrid junction 18 produces signals representing # + # and # - # which are applied via detectors 28, 29, to a difference circuit 30, and the output from the latter is compared in phase in circuit 34 with a signal of frequency f to give a tracking signal. The embodiment effects tracking in azimuth and elevation and the invention avoids the necessity for precise gain and phase equalization of parallel signal channels. A # signal from a further detector 27 affords gain control of amplifiers 23, 24, but exact gain equalization of channels 21, 23, 28 and 22, 24, 29 is not essential and it is stated that the system will continue to operate, though with reduced tracking efficiency, if either of such channels fails. The azimuth 7 and elevation 5 R.F. error signals are modulated by applying them via respective space-quadrature rectangular waveguide inputs 11, 10 to a section of circular waveguide 9, output being taken from a hook-shaped probe 14 rotated at frequency f by a motor 15 energized from generator 16.

column12: Process for making high molecular weight tetrapolymer and articles produced therefrom
column13: A process and articles for continuously making a tetrapolymer can use two reactors connected in series with two saturated hydrocarbon streams, two injections of ethylene monomer, two injections of propylene monomer, and two injections of two different non-conjugated diene monomers simultaneously. Also, the process has a metallocene catalyst and a metallocene co-catalyst in the first reactor and a Ziegler-Natta catalyst, a Ziegler-Natta co-catalyst, and optionally a promoter in the second reactor. This process allows for the creation of products with high molecular weights while utilizing continuous flow reactors in series. The process allows for manufacture of anti-vibration articles made from the high molecular weight tetrapolymers.

column12: Methods and system for enhanced RFID direction finding
column13: At least some embodiments of the present invention are directed to RFID reader systems configured to estimate a directional bearing of an RFID tag. In an embodiment, the present invention is an RFID system configured in a way that upon a detection of a variance in the direction of a maximum RSSI value for a given RFID tag in response to a plurality of interrogation signals transmitted by an RFID reader over a respective plurality of different directions, the RFID reader retransmits the plurality of interrogation signals over the respective plurality of different directions with successively lower power levels until the only response(s) being received no longer exhibit the previously detected variance.

column12: Penile prosthesis with improved fluid control.
column13: A surgically implantable prosthesis for the treatment of penile erectile impotence in male patients. The device comprises at least one elongated cylinder (1) implanted within one of the corpora cavernosa of the penis. The flexible, distal end (2) of the cylinder is adapted to rigidize upon being filled with pressurizing fluid. The rear tip or proximal end (4) of the cylinder is formed to provide a chamber (12) which serves as a fluid reservoir. Valve means (14.15,16) contained within the flexible, distal end section of the cylinder, for conveniently accessible manual manipulation is utilized to selectively control fluid flow between the rear tip reservoir and the distal end of the cylinder. The prosthesis further includes a manually operable pump means (4, 46) utilized to transfer pressurized fluid from the rear tip reservoir to the distal end of the cylinder in order to achieve an erection. The walls of the rear tip reservoir itself may serve as the pump means, or a separate pump (68) may be implanted within the scrotum.

column12: PURIFICATION OF NEUROTROPHINS
column13: 1. A process to isolate a neurotrophin from a mixture containing variants of that neurotrophin that can include a misfolded variant, an incorrectly proteolytically processed variant, or a glycosylation variant of that neurotrophin, comprising a). loading the mixture onto a hydrophobic interaction chromatography resin, b). eluting the neurotrophin from the resin with an elution buffer under conditions in which the neurotrophin separates from the variant, and c). collecting neutrophin. 2. The process of claim 1, in which the resin comprises a phenyl functional group. 3. The process of claim 1, wherein the mixture loaded onto the hydrophobic interaction chromatography resin has a pH of 5 to 8. 4. The process of claim 1, wherein the mixture loaded onto the resin has a salt concentration of 0.5M to 3M. 5. column12: Nuclear Reactor Fuel Handling Arrangements
column13: 1,169,214. Fuelling reactors. ENGLISH ELECTRIC CO. Ltd. 30 March, 1967 [1 April, 1966], No. 14466/66. Heading G6C. A fuel handling system for a gas-cooled reactor employing fuel stringer assemblies enables: (a) the storage of irradiated fuel elements within the reactor shielding until the radiation reaches a low level; (b) the transport of fuel elements to or from the reactor ; and (c) the shuffling of the fuel elements of a stringer assembly. As shown, the shielding 10 has a file cap 11 over which moves a fuelling machine (not shown), the reactor (not shown) being to the left of the drawings. A rotatable carousel 12 driven by a unit 16 has tubes 13 closed at their lower ends by removable gaps 44, each tube being able to accommodate a fuel stringer assembly. A magazine 18 independently rotatable by the unit 16 has tubes 19 closed at their lower ends each able to accommodate one fuel element, the magazine also having a through tube 70. A standpipe 20 closable by a plug 23 enables a stringer assembly to be transferred between the fuelling machine and a carousel tube 13. As shown in Fig. 2, each stringer assembly 50 includes a plug 52 releasably connected to a tie rod 55 by a clamping device 53 engaging the rod head 54, the lower end 56 of the rod supporting through a spider 57 a plurality of fuel elements 59 and bottom and top reflectors 58, 60. Each fuel element 59 comprises outer and inner graphite sleeves 61, 62 and fuel pins 63 arranged between spacers 64. When an irradiated stringer assembly has been lowered into a tube 13 in which it is supported by a ring 69 the tie rod 55 may be released by an hydraulic unit 72 operating a plunger 65 so that the rod falls on to a closed gate valve 41, a gripping device 43 operates to grip the rod and a cutting unit 42 operates to cut the rod. The valve 41 opens to allow the cut off portion of the rod to drop into a space 25. The device 43, unit 42 and valve 41 continue this sequence of operations automatically until the whole of the rod 55 has been cut up. Should the tie rod 55 become jammed it can be forcibly moved downwards by vertical movement of the gripping device 43 between the dash-line and solid line positions. The fuel elements 59 and sleeves 58, 60 and. spider 57 are cooled by a gas flow through the carousel and after the radiation has declined to a safe level they are transferred to a flask 38. To this end the components 57, 58, 59, 60 are lifted singly by a grab 22 into the magazine tubes 19 by appropriate rotation of the carousel and magazine. A turret 28 is rotated to align a discharge duct 32 with a duct 26 and the duct 32 is connected to the flask 38. The components 57, 58, 59, 60 are lifted singly from the magazine by the grab 22 and then lowered through the tube 70 and an empty tube 13 from which the gag 44 has been removed, the carousel and magazine being appropriately rotated. For a shuffling operation the tie rod is cut up and the other components of the fuel stringer assembly are stored to the magazine tubes 19 as before. A new tie rod is introduced by raising it in stages by a jack 37 through a loading tube 34 into a carousel tube 13. At each stage a particular component of the stringer assembly is lowered on to the rod by the grab 22 until the assembly is complete, the shuffling being determined by the order in which the components are selected from the magazine.

column12: ELECTROSTATICALLY AUGMENTED FIBER BED SEPARATOR
column13: C-17-21-3203 ELECTROSTATICALLY AUGMENTED FIBER BED SEPARATOR ABSTRACT A method and apparatus for removal of particulates from gas streams with high collection efficiency on even submicron particulates. The apparatus includes a grounded fiber bed of 50 to 1000 micron average diameter fibers packed to a bed voidage of at least 90%, an electro-static or ionizing field means upstream of the fiber bed to place an electrical charge on the particulates, and irrigation means for the fiber bed, and optionally the grounded electrodes of the electrostatic means as well, to flush collected particulates from the fiber bed and optionally from the grounded electrodes. The method is suitable for separation of any particulates but is particu-larly advantageous for separation of insoluble solid particulates from gas streams at high bed velocities of from 6 to 15 or more feet per second (i.e., 1.8 to 4.6 or more meters per second). The preferred fiber bed is of 100 to 500 micron diameter, and advantageously 100 to 250 micron diameter, glass fibers. In operation, particulates are charged in the electrostatic means and the charged particulates are collected in the fiber bed where the elec-trical charge is dissipated through the irrigating liquid/particulates mixture so that no significant space charge effect is allowed to develop in the fibers of the fiber bed and re-entrainment of particulates is avoided.

column12: Process for making high molecular weight tetrapolymer and articles produced therefrom
column13: A process and articles for continuously making a tetrapolymer using two reactors connected in series with two saturated hydrocarbon streams, two injections of ethylene monomer, two injections of propylene monomer, and two injections of two different non-conjugated diene monomers simultaneously with two metallocene catalysts and two metallocene co-catalysts. This process allows for the creation of products with high molecular weights while utilizing continuous flow reactors in series, preventing an additional blending step. The process allows for manufacture of anti-vibration articles made by the tetrapolymers.

column12: METHODS AND SYSTEM FOR ENHANCED RFID DIRECTION FINDING
column13: At least some embodiments of the present invention are directed to RFID reader systems configured to estimate a directional bearing of an RFID tag. In an embodiment, the present invention is an RFID system configured in a way that upon a detection of a variance in the direction of a maximum RSSI value for a given RFID tag in response to a plurality of interrogation signals transmitted by an RFID reader over a respective plurality of different directions, the RFID reader retransmits the plurality of interrogation signals over the respective plurality of different directions with successively lower power levels until the only response(s) being received no longer exhibit the previously detected variance.

column12: Rotary disc valve
column13: 1,183,534. Valves. UNIVERSAL OIL PRODUCTS CO. 5 June, 1967 [9 June, 1966], No. 25802/67. Heading F2V. A rotary disc selector valve comprises a stator 11, which has formed therein twenty-four ports 25 equally spaced around the circumference, and five concentric circular grooves A, B, C, D and E, and a rotor 15 which is biased on to the stator by fluid pressure applied through duct 24 and has five crossover tubes (27, 28, 29, 30, Figs. 2 and 3, not shown) and 31 each one communicating with one groove and one of five ports (32-36, Fig. 3) spaced around the circumference of the rotor, each of the grooves being supplied with fluid through a line 26 such that it can be transferred from the groove, via the corresponding crossover tube to corresponding port in the rotor and hence to the selected port in the stator. Disposed between the stator and rotor, and fixed to the latter, is a plastics liner 16 having formed therein five apertures to correspond with the rotor ports and nineteen recesses 50 each one corresponding to one of the non-selected stator ports, the recesses being of slightly larger diameter than the stator ports and being positioned slightly radially inwardly toward the axis of rotation of the rotor. Within each such recess there is mounted a relatively rigid plate-like reinforcing member 51 comprising a metallic or hard plastics plate 53, which may be perforated, secured to the rotor 15 by machine screws 55 and coated with a layer of plastics material, the outer surface 56 of the plate 15 being spaced inwardly from the surface 57 of the plastics liner 16. Rotation of the rotor, as by shafts 17 and 22 coupled together by a flexible coupling member 21, brings each groove into communication with one stator port, the remaining stator ports being covered by the recesses which, by virtue of their construction, serve to prevent distortion of the liner 16 at or over these non-selected ports. In an alternative embodiment (Figs. 7 and 8, not shown) there is provided in the region of and directly over each reinforcing member 51, a set of passageways (71) which communicate with a central pressure relief vent (72), extending through the member, the arrangement serving to minimize deformation of the liner as due to accumulation of pressure between the liner and rotor.

column12: PROCEDES ET SYSTEME POUR LA RECHERCHE DE DIRECTION D'ETIQUETTE RFID AMELIOREE
column13: P rocédés et système pour la recherche de direction d'étiquette RFID améliorée Au moins certains modes de réalisation de la présente invention concernent des systèmes de lecteur RFID configurés pour estimer un relèvement directionnel d'une étiquette RFID. Dans un mode de réalisation, la présente invention est un système RFID configuré de manière à ce que, lors d'une détection d'une variance dans la direction d'une valeur de RSSI maximum pour une étiquette RFID donnée en réponse à une pluralité de signaux d'interrogation transmis par un lecteur RFID (20) dans une pluralité respective de directions différentes, le lecteur RFID (20) retransmette la pluralité de signaux d'interrogation dans la pluralité respective de directions différentes avec des niveaux de puissance successivement inférieurs jusqu'à ce que la seule réponse reçue ne présente plus la variance détectée précédemment. column12: Methods and system for enhanced RFID direction finding
column13: At least some embodiments of the present invention are directed to RFID reader systems configured to estimate a directional bearing of an RFID tag. In an embodiment, the present invention is an RFID system configured in a way that upon a detection of a variance in the direction of a maximum RSSI value for a given RFID tag in response to a plurality of interrogation signals transmitted by an RFID reader over a respective plurality of different directions, the RFID reader retransmits the plurality of interrogation signals over the respective plurality of different directions with successively lower power levels until the only response(s) being received no longer exhibit the previously detected variance.
